\begin_layout Section
A Quartic Curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Z}[x,y]\slash f$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f=(y-x^{2}+5x-5)(y+x^{2}-5x+5)-1=uv-1\label{eq:antilocal1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where we set 
\begin_inset Formula $u=y-x^{2}+5x-5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=y+x^{2}-5x+5$
\end_inset

.
 Note that from the expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we see that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 are units in 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Here we are describing 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 as a quotient of a polynomial ring, but we can also describe it as a finite
 module extension over a polynomial ring.
 Namely, we can write it as 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\mathbb{Z}[y][\sqrt{g}]$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f=y^{2}-(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)=y^{2}-g,\label{eq:antilocal2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $g=(x-1)(x-2)(x-3)(x-4)$
\end_inset

.
 The expression of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is nice because we can read off information like the discriminant of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}[y]$
\end_inset

.
 Basically from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal2})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we can read off useful information of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 viewed as a finite module extension, whereas from 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

(
\backslash
ref{eq:antilocal1})
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we can read off useful information of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 viewed as a quotient.
 Both expressions give rise to the same ring 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 at the end of the day.
 Next we set 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

.
 To get an idea of what 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 looks like, we consider the canonical morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 For each positive prime 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we obtain the fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{p}=X_{\mathbb{F}_{p}}$
\end_inset

 of this canonical morphism at the prime ideal 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle p\rangle$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{p}=\mathrm{Spec}(\mathbb{F}_{p}\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}A)=\mathrm{Spec}(\mathbb{F}_{p}[x,y]\slash f).
\]

\end_inset

We also obtain the fiber 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{0}=X_{\mathbb{Q}}$
\end_inset

 of this canonical morphism at the generic point 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle0\rangle$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{\mathbb{Q}}=\mathrm{Spec}(\mathbb{Q}\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}A)=\mathrm{Spec}(\mathbb{Q}[x,y]\slash f).
\]

\end_inset

Note 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbb{Q}}$
\end_inset

 is just the pullback of the morphism 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Q}\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the canonical map 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 We can specialize even further by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{K}$
\end_inset

 to be the pullback of the composite 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,K\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Q}\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 with respect to the canonical map 
\begin_inset Formula $X\to\mathrm{Spec}\,\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $K\slash\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

 is some field extension:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{K}=\mathrm{Spec}(K\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}A)=\mathrm{Spec}(K[x,y]\slash f).
\]

\end_inset

The closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{K}$
\end_inset

 correspond to the maximal ideals of 
\begin_inset Formula $K[x,y]\slash f$
\end_inset

, and when 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is algebraically closed, these correspond to the points of the variety
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{V}_{K}(f)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
hfill
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

We now consider 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbb{R}}=\mathrm{Spec}(\mathbb{R}[x,y]\slash f)$
\end_inset

, viewed as an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-scheme (thus the canonical morphism is 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbb{R}}\to\mathrm{Spec\,}\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

).
 To get an idea of what 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

 looks like, we shall look at its 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

-valued points 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{\mathbb{R}}(\mathbb{R})=\mathrm{V}_{\mathbb{R}}(f)=C$
\end_inset

 pictured below:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


