\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 also has a generic point 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 corresponding to the zero ideal of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 The closed points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 correspond to the points of the affine open set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

: they have the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathfrak{p}_{(a,b),[1:t]}=\langle x-a,y-b,v-t\rangle
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,t\in\Bbbk$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $b^{2}=a^{3}+a^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $at=b$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}=a+1$
\end_inset

.
 Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, then we automatically get 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{2}=a+1$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\Bbbk=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 we can visualize the points of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Spec}\,A$
\end_inset

 as below:
\end_layout

