\end_inset

In particular, for 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq0$
\end_inset

, the prime 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{(a,b),[1:t]}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\in X$
\end_inset

 together with the unique line 
\begin_inset Formula $y=tx$
\end_inset

 that passes through that point and the origin, where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 represents the slope of that line.
 There are two points lying over the origin: namely 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{(0,0),[1:1]}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{p}_{(0,0),[1:-1]}$
\end_inset

, corresponding to the origin 
\begin_inset Formula $(0,0)\in V$
\end_inset

 together with the lines 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-x$
\end_inset

 respectively.
 The map 
\begin_inset Formula $\iota\colon R\to A$
\end_inset

 induces a continuous map 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\mathrm{a}}\iota\colon\mathrm{Spec}\,A\to\mathrm{Spec}\,R$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
^{\mathrm{a}}\iota(\mathfrak{p}_{(a,b),[1,t]})=\mathfrak{p}_{(a,b)}.
\]

\end_inset

This corresponds to the projection map 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi\colon U\to X$
\end_inset

 given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi(a,b,t)=(a,b).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that in the image above there are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

missing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 points.
 For instance, we drew a vertical dashed line in the image above; it should
 correspond to the line 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, but it has nowhere to go under this projection.
 In fact, this missing line corresponds to the extra point in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{Proj}(\mathrm{bl}(R))$
\end_inset

 which doesn't belong to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

